<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title></title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">RCH0012</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">BASW </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">BASW’s submission to the Education Committee Inquiry on Residential Children’s Homes</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">BASW is the UK professional association for social work, led by and accountable to a growing population of approximately 15,000 social worker members.  Our members work in frontline, management, research and academic positions in all social work settings across the UK.  BASW members share a collective commitment to those values and principles that will secure the best possible outcomes for children and young people, adults, families and communities.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Terms of Reference of the Inquiry</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Whether the DfE’s proposed reforms to the regulation of residential children’s homes are appropriate and sufficient</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Whether the reforms are likely to prove effective or further measures are needed</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Background Information</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">BASW is very committed to improving policy and practice to benefit the thousands of children in England who are currently looked after by local authorities.  BASW is a member of the Alliance for Children in Care and Care Leavers which is an influential group of principally third sector organisations promoting the rights of looked after children and care leavers largely through campaigning.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">BASW is also a member of the RCC (Refugee Children’s Consortium) which helps us to maintain a specific focus on unaccompanied migrant children and understand their experiences of services.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">BASW has also been proactive in raising the profile of children who are vulnerable to sexual exploitation through our recent involvement in  the roundtable discussions led by the DPP in respect of improving the experience of child witnesses who have been sexually abused when giving their evidence and we submitted a response to the recent CPS consultation- Interim Guidelines on Prosecuting Cases of Child Sexual Abuse.  We were also a member of the advisory group for the University of Bedfordshire who produced the Comic Relief sponsored research </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">What</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">s Going On to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">S</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">afeguard </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">hildren and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Y</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">oung </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">P</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">eople from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">S</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">exual </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">E</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">xploitation </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">published in October 2011</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Finally, many BASW members are IROs and as well as conducting our own survey last year about their experiences of practice we </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">also a member of the NCB advisory group which</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> has</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> produced</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the initial</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">report - </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The role of Independent Reviewing Officers (IROs) in England -Findings from a national survey </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in August 2013</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (the final report to be released in December 2013).</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What is the s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">tarting point </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">for using residential children’s homes?</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Whilst we very much welcome the Government giving higher priority to the needs of children in residential care we do not think that the approach outlined in the three consultation documents is necessarily coherent enough to produce the kind of change we would all like to see for this group of children in the care population.  The proposals contained in the consultations are largely reactive and remedial and it is our contention that they miss the point.  If we are going to devise an effective strategy in England about residential children’s homes then surely the first question needs to be what is their purpose?  Are they merely a placement of last resort to hold young people until they are old enough to leave care?  The profile of children in residential care was certainly raised by some of the recent scandals concerning child sexual exploitation by gangs.  We know that the average age of a young person placed in a children’s home is fifteen and a half and on average their placement lasts 7 months.   This led the former children’s minister to question whether we were using this resource in the most effective way.   Tim Loughton, when giving evidence to the APPG inquiry about children who go missing said that the first step had to be to break with an ‘out of sight out of mind culture’ and to make a children’s home a placement of first choice.  We are not clear if that is the political prerogative given that Michael Gove is quoted in the Daily Telegraph on 13 September 2013 as saying: </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">“Those rescued from neglectful homes, and who have not found stable, loving families to care for them, should find security and support in children’s homes where they can enjoy a fresh start.” </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This implies that children’s homes are second best and that the destination of all children in the care system should be with alternative families.   The danger is that we end up promoting a ‘one size fits all’ approach rather than looking at the differing needs of children and young people who come into care to determine what the best provision is for them.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It is therefore important that we nail our colours to the mast in England and present an unambiguous, philosophical basis that underpins how and why we use residential children’s homes.  There is good research available that we can draw on to help us to effectively develop our practice in this area such as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What Works in Residential Child Care A review of research evidence and the practical considerations (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Roger Clough, Roger Bullock, Adrian Ward 2006) as well as all the valuable reports produced by the Children’s Rights Director, Roger Morgan over the years, critically, providing us with the views of young people themselves.  It is time to break with a ‘deficit’ model and move to one of bringing value.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It would be helpful to also see what we could usefully learn from our colleagues in other parts of the UK – for example, Scotland recently produced a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> National Residential Child Care Initiative</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> which aims</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to make its children's homes the first and best choice for young people who have high level needs. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">BASW’s key issues with the reforms</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It is essential that the messaging is right and not confused.  Government ministers have chided local authorities for placing children outside of their locations-</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">“ almost half of children are placed in homes outside their local authority areas, and over a third are sent more than 20 miles from home. That is indefensible.”</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (Gove, Daily Telegraph 13 September 2013)</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Nevertheless, there are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">sometimes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> good reasons for placing children outside of their localities which are in their best interests; for example, children who are at risk from their traffickers.  Politicians need to adopt a more balanced and evidence based approach to these issues rather than again a ‘broad brush approach’.   After all, many examples of good practice were shared at the APPG inquiry on children who go missing which shed light on some of the complexities.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The reforms completely fail to address issues of ‘market forces’.  Who actually owns the homes and decides where they are located.  Certainly, not the professionals on the ground or even the local authorities.  The main focus of the consultations appears to be about confronting the practice of local authorities and taking care home managers to task but not the actual owners who we know are largely </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">private equity firms and property dealers who are not being held to account even though their profits come out of the public purse.  Surely, there is a moral and ethical debate to be had here about divergence between huge profit margins and in some cases, a lack of value for money in terms of children, their welfare and their outcomes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There is a need for  strategic planning around the provision of children’s residential  care rather than the provider led ad hoc approach  we have at the moment – </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">a)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">what do we need b)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">why do we need it  c)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">where do we need it  d)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">who should provide it e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">)what qualifications and on-going support does the workforce need f)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">what workforce planning is needed to achieve this g)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">when should it be achieved by  h)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">how do we know it has changed practice i)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">how do we involve all stakeholders including children and young people in planning, implementation and evaluation.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  The objective should be to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> achieve a whole</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">sale</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> change in culture</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in attitudes towards residential care being a last resort to an expectation that children should have a quality, caring experience in a home environment.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It is important that we learn how to improve practice by looking at international models and their efficacy.  BASW is a member of the IFSW (International Federation of Social Workers) and certainly benefits from having a discourse about social work beyond the confines of the UK.  BASW is therefore, extremely disappointed that social pedagogy is not even mentioned in any of the three documents given the work that was done by the DCSF on this a few years ago.  The study that emerged from it </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Raising the Bar? An Evaluation of the Social Pedagogy Pilot Programme in Children’s Residential Homes </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">(Berridge </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">et al.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">, 2011)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> certainly raised expectations in the sector that this is something that would be further developed in England given the clear benefits it brings to children and young people in residential care particularly, in terms of meeting their therapeutic needs.  We consider this to be a missed opportunity and we urge the Government to put social pedagogy back on the table.  Residential children’s homes as we know are a costly provision but if we want to spend the money well to improve outcomes for these young people this would be an excellent place to make an investment.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Related to the previous point are the i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ssue</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> about </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">improving the training and qualification of residential children’s workers.  Again, consideration should also be given to widely promoting a graduate qualification in social pedagogy that could make a fundamental difference to the quality of care received by children and also help to solve difficulties related to a transient workforce. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> We are aware that the CWDC did some work a few years ago on developing level 5 standards for practitioners and we wonder what has happened to that as the evaluation showed that these were also extremely effective in helping individuals to reflect on their practice and have a better contextual understanding of why children come into care, their backgrounds etc.  It is important that we don’t lose these promising initiatives but build on them.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A range of standards and qualifications at different levels would provide a much needed career structure, contribute to staff retention and most importantly improve practice in this complex and challenging area of work.  Qualifications for registered managers and skills in professional supervision for all supervisors are essential.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Policy addressing residential children’s homes needs to be joined up with a range of other initiatives such as those taken to address the education of looked after children. The creation of virtual school heads is very welcome and we hope the provisions in the Children and Families Bill will help this role to have much greater prominence and reach than it currently has.  On that note, we are astounded that the draft proposals on children who go missing from care do not even mention  the role of education yet they are an essential partner in supporting the needs of looked after children.  This makes a nonsense of the concept of key agencies working together.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">mproving the situation of children in residential care</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> must be part of an overarching strategy that is also concerned with what happens to young people once they leave care as highlighted in the Still o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ur </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hildren </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">briefing for the House of Commons Report Stage of the Children and Families Bill (May 2013</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">). </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">BASW therefore supports the proposed amendment to the bill proposed by</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the Fostering Network and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Earl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Listowel </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to enable those in care</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> up to the age of 25 to have either the full time or part time support of their carers in order to align more with the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">experience of most young people who on</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> average </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">remain with their families until </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">24 years of age.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In respect of children and young people at risk of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">child sexual exploitation it is vital that there is good communication between Government departments i.e. the DfE needs to have links with the CPS/DPP in order to determine how children and young people in care can be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">protect</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ed in different parts of the system.  This very much applies to young people in care who get into trouble and find themselves in the youth justice system under the auspices of the ministry of justice.  It is vital that the focus on the child does not get lost and as Eileen Munro emphasises the central discourse is the child’s journey (irrespective of which system they may find themselves in).  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We think that there is some divergence between on the one hand, wanting to promote a children’s rights approach yet as a result of the Family Justice Review the proposal in the Children and Families Bill is that courts should be curtailed from scrutinising local authority care plans.  We think that this approach is likely to be highly problematic given that we already know that IROs are currently struggling with their workloads which in many cases greatly exceed what is stipulated in the handbook and of course, the question of their ability to be sufficiently independent from the local authority when  providing their views is debatable.  The results from BASW’s survey certainly painted a mixed picture in this respect.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">BASW very much welcomes the proposals in the Children and Families Bill to make the current Children’s Commissioner in England a rights based commissioner as this is long overdue.  Equally, we can understand the logic of absorbing the role of the Children’s Rights Director into the OCC.  As we have already stated, we consider the role and work produced by the CRD to be very important and so these changes do raise issues about resources.  We would like some assurances that the current budget of the CRD would not be compromised by this transfer but if anything strengthened.  We look forward to seeing more detail on this in terms of both the functions and remit of the role as well as the resource issue.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We were very surprised that the consultation on the statutory guidance on children who run away and go missing from care or home did not even contain a section exploring resource implications</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  How can any of the proposals be effective if they cannot be properly implemented?  We know that in relation to cse and children who go missing for example, the post code lottery is very significant, in terms of the availability of specialist resources and support being piecemeal.  Moreover, many </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> under even greater pressure in terms of their survival because of cuts in public spending.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">IROs should in many respects, be a pivotal part of the reforms given that they are also a critical factor in ensuring</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> local authorities comply with their duties to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">looked after children in terms of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">care planning etc </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">yet there is nothing in these documents to strengthen their role to make it more effective but rather</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> it is our fear that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the proposals will just make greater demands on a resource that is already </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> severely </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">over stretched.  This will inevitably fuel the blame culture. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We cannot see how the DfE proposals will improve the current situation affecting one of the most vulnerable groups of children at the greatest risk of going missing from care -</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">unaccompanied migrant children. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> We know that these children are likely to go missing very early following their admission into care and many are never recovered which is sobering.  Whilst there various </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">strategies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in place we know that the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> implementation </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">weak</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> as highlighted in a recent report</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  This work needs to be given a much higher priority which requires adequate resources</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and training and support for all professionals</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  It is vital that specialist resource</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s that are effective are developed </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for this vulnerable group such as specialist foster placements.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Commissioning and models of procurement </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">re clearly major issues that need to be grappled in respect of residential children’s homes.  BASW believes that having commissioners working in local authority children’s services from a social work background makes an enormous difference in terms of the promotion of a more child centred culture</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We know that in practice, only a tiny minority of commissioners hold social work qualifications</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rocurement </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">should not </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">only</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> concerned with finding </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cheapest </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">option but must start by evaluating the quality and appropriateness of a children’s home</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. There is currently a review of commissioning standards being undertaken by S</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">kills </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">f</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">or </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&amp; D</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">evelopment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and we have recommended that social work skills and understanding are essential for effective commissioning.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The issue of data collection</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (which was highlighted in the consultation on children who run away and go missing from care or home)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">very important on</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> local, regional and national scale.  It needs to happen effectively on all of these levels so</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> we </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">have a much more developed understanding of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is happening. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We endorse the view that the accommodation needs of 16 and 17 year olds living independently has to be addressed.  We know from research that this is a very vulnerable group of young people.  There are some good examples of provision such as projects run by the third sector  but sadly they are not universally available and are also often subject to time limited funding  and therefore are vulnerable to closure.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There is a risk that some of the proposals contained in the consultation on reforming children’s homes could end up with ‘unintended consequences’, for example, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">guidance </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">concerning</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the ‘safe location’ of Homes </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">could be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">used to prevent provision being built in areas which are relatively safe given that there is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">prejudice</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> against such resources</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> for vulnerable children.  Sadly, NIMBY lobbyists can exert a lot of power and influence in their localities.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Finally, these reforms need to pay heed to lessons from</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Munro </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">review </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">about overly bureaucracy approaches not having the desired outcomes – mechanistic approaches don’t work but </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">there </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">seems to be a heavy reliance on them</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in the three documents.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>